UML:TaggedValue.value:
The configuration file shall be written in XML format.
This allows easy transformation via XML Style Sheets for other programs (e.g. with the xsltproc tool).

In addition to any other requirements, the following shall be emitted on a string match from the configuration file.  
  • The file where the match was found, should more than one file be searched. In case there is only one file being searched, or if supported STDIN, no filename needs to be printed.
  • The Group where the string match was made.
  • Metadata provided with the configuration file for the match.

Simple text files without timestamps shall be supported.
Upon a hit, the line number shall be printed.

The XML entry for a search string shall also support some attributes that provide extra metadata, used to document statistics or to identify responsible domains. Such metadata includes:
  • Responsible name (string), as a domain name, person name, email address.
  • Issue reference (string), for mapping to a ticket number (Elvis, Jira, QC, ChangeList, etc.)

UML:ClassifierRole.name: Specifying Log Files as Auxillary File

UML:TaggedValue.value:
A specific command line option shall be provided that loads a list of files to parse.
/files:filename.txt /f:filename.txt

A simple file format shall be used for specifying log files. This file shall be a text file with each line containing a relative or an absolute path to a file.
No quotes are required as part of the file.
The file shall be interpreted in UTF-8 format with no Byte Order Marks.
The tool shall support a command line environment so it can be put in windows script files.

Logfiles for scanning shall be on the command line without an option parameter. The command line option(s) shall support filesystem "globbing".
Example: traceparse *.cnl

A file that can be included is the same format as a normal configuration file.
This allows multiple domains to maintain their own configuration file, in addition to define a heirarchy in the project that would include such files.

There shall be an XML Schema associated with the configuration file.
This allows to check for correctness, as well as to clearly specify the format for third parties for compatibility with other tools (e.g. HTA, or script based search tools).

The V850 raw log files, as recorded directly from the serial port shall be supported when available in the Automation Framework. The Automation Framework has work ongoing to support this, but it is not currently supported.
Upon a hit, the Device timestamp, module and log line shall be printed.
In case the program is started from the command line (there is at least one command line parameter provided), the output of the searches shall be emitted on the command console.

An XML line shall support a single search string. A search string doesn't need to be a full regular expression, but should support simple substitution rules, such as with a DFA (Deterministic Finite Automaton).
For example, see http://www.codeproject.com/Articles/677580/Combined-Regular-Expression-Search
The XML file shall support Groups. A group is a collection of search strings in the XML tree structure.

The search string shall support at a minimum the following operators:
  • Kleen Star(*) and +
  • Alternation (|)
  • Optional Operator(?)
  • Parentheses

GnLog TRC files shall be supported. The Automation Framework supports reading TRC files.
Upon a hit, the PC timestamp, Device Timestamp, Console, Process Name, Scope shall be printed.
The following file formats shall be supported.

The configuration file shall support including other configuration files.
The XML tag for including shall be at a top level. Including at a group level should not be supported.
The tool shall support Windows specific options, e.g. /x:value or /xyz:value

Teraterm files with timestamps shall be supported. The Automation Framework supports reading TeraTerm files.
Upon a hit, the line number and timestamp shall be printed.
If the option /help or /? or /h is provided, the tool shall emit on the command prompt the usage of the tool.

GnLog Multicore format files (binary) shall be supported. The Automation Framework supports reading GnLog files.
Upon a hit, the PC timestamp, Device Timestamp, Console, Process Name, Scope and the text line shall be printed.

The tool shall support outputting results in a simple XML format instead of the console.
Such a format can be easily converted using a stylesheet with a predefined namespace.

Given a single group, with an arbitrary number of search strings, the search time shall be generally independent of the number of search strings.
To achieve this, standard regular expressions cannot be used, other systems, such as deterministic finite automaton should be used.

It shall be possible to specify on the command line, a summary result containing the number of times a particular search instance was found.
The output should be in a format that allows the user to determine the precise rule affected.
The default for this option is disabled due to the potential high number of entries.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: Occurrence Counting for a Single Entry

UML:TaggedValue.value:
It shall be possible to specify on the command line specific rules that should be counted.
The option may be provided multiple times (one per rule), or singly, with a comma separated list of rules.
The default for this option is no rules.

Occurrence counting can assist with the quick analysis.
Although counts can be done automatically with technologies such as XML, this option doesn't exist for free text output (such as console output).
A user can use this output for statistics (e.g. in special cases, the total number of lifecycles). While the tool itself doesn't know the concept of a new lifecycle, the configuration writer does.
A command line option shall be provided to customise the output format.
A tool shall be created that parses through various log files looking for predetermined strings and patterns.
The results shall be emitted in a format compatible with the user chosen output (on the console in tabular form, or as a summary section in the output XML).
Windows 7 SP1 or later shall be used for development, with Visual Studio 2012 (Express Edition) or Visual Studio 2013 (Express or Community Edition)
.NET Framework, version 4.0 shall be supported on current supported Windows platforms.
Unit Test Cases shall be written for the various components of the Trace Scanner tool.
